Forbes 2025 World's Best Banks List

EDITED BY RACHEL RABKIN PEACHMAN
APRIL 09, 2025, 10:00 AM
  • Amid the recent onslaught of tariffs issued by President Donald Trump, plummeting global markets, and widespread economic uncertainty, consumers around the world may be more intent than ever on choosing a bank they can trust. But assessing which banks can meet clients’ needs is no simple feat.
    To make it easier for consumers to choose a financial institution, Forbes—in partnership with market research firm Statista—ranked the World’s Best Banks based on survey responses from more than 50,000 people across 34 countries in 17 different languages. From October 2024 through December 2024 survey participants were asked to evaluate banks where they currently have a checking or savings account, where they’ve had an account within the past three years, or that they knew through family or friends. Any bank offering a checking or savings account was eligible; United States credit unions were not.
    Respondents shared their level of satisfaction with each bank, as well as how likely they would be to recommend it to others. Participants also rated each bank on five criteria: trustworthiness, terms and conditions (such as fees and rates), customer service (wait times and helpfulness of employees), digital services (ease of using online tools), and quality of financial advice. Lastly, respondents were asked to rank these five criteria on their importance to them, and the categories were weighted accordingly. Trustworthiness—perhaps unsurprisingly—was deemed the most important aspect of a bank among participants across all countries.
    Ultimately, all of these survey elements were factored into a scoring system, with lower weights given to responses from former customers (within the last three years) and people who knew the bank through family and friends as opposed to responses from current customers, which were given the highest weight. The analysis also included last year’s results at a lower weight to account for the banks’ performance over time. All told, the banks with the highest final scores in their countries made our ranking, which consists of 385 banks around the globe. (Note that the number of banks listed in each country varies according to the country’s population and the size of its banking sector.)
    Notably, 265 banks on last year’s list made the list again this year, highlighting a strong showing of consistently high-performing banks. And an impressive 18 banks retained their first-place rank in each of their countries. To find out more about these banks along with all the other listees, see our full ranking of 385 banks directly below.

    PT Bank Rakyat Indonesia (Persero) Tbk is a holding company, which engages in the provision of financial services.
